<p><b>Memorial Day</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Federal_holidays_in_the_United_States" title="Federal holidays in the United States">United States federal holiday</a> observed on the last Monday of May (on May 25 in 2009). Formerly known as <b>Decoration Day</b>, it commemorates U.S. men and women who died while in <a href="/wiki/Military_service" title="Military service">military service</a> to their country. First enacted to honor <a href="/wiki/Union_Army" title="Union Army">Union</a> soldiers of the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a> (it is celebrated near the day of reunification after the civil war), it was expanded after <a href="/wiki/World_War_I" title="World War I">World War I</a> to include American casualties of any war or military action.</p>
